          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0661P0-07086'>
        <a name='S5LV0661P0_20040525_GCR_87'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/ms-christine-crawley' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040525_GCR_87' title='Link to this speech by Ms Christine Crawley' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/ms-christine-crawley" title="Ms Christine Crawley">Baroness Crawley</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            The noble Baroness is right: we can see such advertisements each week, should we be looking for them. They are not against the law because there is an exception in the <a href="/acts/sex-discrimination-act-1975">Sex Discrimination Act 1975</a> that allows married couples to be considered for such jobs. I used the public house example, but the noble Baroness is right to say that it could apply to a cook and gardener or a housekeeper and gardener. It is the same thing. As the legislation is drafted, there would be a read-across from the legality of the advertisement in <span class="italic">The Lady</span> saying "married couple" to saying "civil partnership".
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0661P0-07087'>
